snippet.textDisplay:
That dessert you mentioned reminds me of sapin-sapin, a multi-layered (hence the name) sticky rice snack. Though it has (usually) 3 colors, all of them taste the same.

A few desserts we usually makes that has jello in it are :

Tapioca : pandan flavored jellies with tapioca balls and young fresh coconut meat (in long strips cut using that tool with like 4 or more holes that's dragged inside the coconut shell to get the meat, idk what it's called). Pandan jellies are cut in small cubes maybe half an inch big. Served chilled.


Another one my mom would make is plain milk jelly with weird stuff added in to it like processed cheese cut in cubes added to the bottom of the container then the jello is poured over it. Other variations are with raisins or roasted peanut (crushed and sprinkled on top when the jelly is almost set).

Not jelly but kinda jelly-like is Maja Blanca, our family don't make this but we buy it from time to time. It's basically like that fried milk recipe using cornstarch instead of jelly to make it set. It's not fried too but served cold but are fine room temp. The difference beside using coconut milk is that sometimes people add corn to it. The common version is plain with crushed toasted peanuts on top.

snippet.textDisplay: I did this a while back! If you are on Facebook you can see my post in the group Show Me Your Aspics. Someone had posted a photo of what they thought was gelatin but it turned out to be soap. Everyone was disappointed, including myself, so I made an actual gelatin PB&J! Glad to see I'm not the only person! Edited to add: I found the peanut butter layer to be the tastiest. I used much more peanut butter and it ended up almost having the texture and flavor of peanut butter fudge. I also used more grape jelly but it still didn't taste strong enough for me. For the "bread" I used sweetened condensed milk and it was delicious! I used gelatin, not agar agar, which might have made some difference. Overall, it was an enjoyable experience, my son LOVED it, and I can say I was just as excited as Emmy was however, my husband thought I was a bit wacky!

snippet.textDisplay: Yeow, dingle berry, when you do any type of Gelatin dish the secret of making it let go of your container is to warm your container by dipping it in hot water for about 15 seconds OR LESS, it depends on how thick, in this case, the glass is. As soon as it lets go put it back in the frig to make sure no more heat gets to the gel.
